Date: 23 May 2002
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Scotsman.com, 23 May 2002 [edited]
<http://www.news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=4723787>

Sir Geoff backs foot and mouth disease warning to World Cup fans
----------------------------------------------------------------
World Cup hat trick hero Sir Geoff Hurst today kicked off a campaign to
warn football fans against bringing back fresh meat bought during the
coming tournament in Korea and Japan.
Launching the Government's campaign, Food and Farming Minister Lord Whitty
said the highest risk from fresh meat was in Korea, where there had been a
recent outbreak of FMD. Britain was anxious to prevent any repetition of
last year's disaster when the disease ravaged farming and the countryside.
Lord Whitty said: "The highest risk is food from South Korea. There are
controls in place and meat products should not be brought back." He said
that any illegal meat, even if partly eaten, could get back into the food
chain. There would be stringent airport checks awaiting fans returning from
Korea, he warned.
[Byline: Vik Iyer, PA News]
